<Base title="Agentfile — ostk governance" description="Define what an agent can do. One file per agent type. Dockerfile for intelligence.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Agentfile</h1>
    <p class="lead">The definition file for one agent. Specifies model, tools, limits, and work scope. One file per agent type.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      An Agentfile describes a single agent — what model it uses, what tools it can call,
      what resources it's allowed to consume, and what work it should pull from the queue.
      Think of it as a Dockerfile for intelligence: it builds the execution context an agent
      runs in, not a filesystem layer.
    </p>
    <p>Run an agent: <code>haystack run path/to/Agentfile</code></p>

    <h2>Minimal example</h2>
    <pre><code>FROM claude-sonnet-4-6
BOOT haystack boot --bail
PROMPT "Fix the failing tests in src/. Run cargo test after each fix."
TOOL sh_run
TOOL ss
LIMIT context_pct 80
LIMIT budget_usd 5
WORK tags=bugfix priority>=P1</code></pre>

    <h2>Directive reference</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Directive</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>FROM</code></td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            Model to use. <code>FROM auto</code> lets the scheduler select the best
            available model at dispatch time based on vault inventory and benchmark scores.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>BOOT</code></td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>
            Command to run before PROMPT loads. Default: <code>haystack boot --bail</code>.
            The <code>--bail</code> flag stops the agent if the kernel reports unhealthy.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>PROMPT</code></td>
          <td>Yes (1+)</td>
          <td>
            System prompt. Inline string or <code>file://path</code> reference.
            Multiple PROMPT directives concatenate in order.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>TOOL</code></td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>
            MCP tool the agent can call. Omit entirely for a read-only agent.
            Tool omission is capability restriction — the agent literally cannot call
            what isn't listed.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>SKILL</code></td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>Skill bundle name. Skills extend the agent with domain knowledge.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>LIMIT</code></td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>
            Resource constraint. <code>LIMIT context_pct 80</code> stops the agent
            from pulling new needles above 80% context. <code>LIMIT budget_usd 5</code>
            caps spend.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>WORK</code></td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>
            Pull filter. <code>WORK tags=rust priority>=P1</code> makes this a
            long-running worker that claims matching needles from the queue.
            Without WORK, the agent is one-shot: it runs once and exits.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>INTERRUPT</code></td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td>Event that wakes a waiting agent. For reactive agents that wait for triggers.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>FROM auto</h2>
    <p>
      <code>FROM auto</code> delegates model selection to the scheduler. At dispatch time,
      the scheduler reads your vault inventory, checks benchmark scores, and selects the
      highest-scoring model for which you have an API key. You configure the candidates
      via your vault; the scheduler picks the best fit.
    </p>
    <p>
      Explicit model selection (<code>FROM claude-opus-4-6</code>) bypasses scheduling
      and pins to a specific model. Use this when the task requires a specific capability.
    </p>

    <h2>BOOT --bail</h2>
    <p>
      <code>haystack boot --bail</code> runs the power-on self test before loading the
      agent's context. If the kernel is unhealthy — stale boot.md, corrupt audit trail,
      identity conflicts — the agent stops cleanly rather than running on bad state.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is the integrity-before-velocity principle at the agent layer. An agent that
      boots from a corrupt state produces corrupt work.
    </p>

    <h2>One Agentfile, one agent type</h2>
    <p>
      An Agentfile describes a single agent. Not a fleet. Not an orchestrator-and-workers.
      One file, one agent type. For fleet composition — multiple agents working together —
      see Fleetfile (coming soon).
    </p>

